                <h4>
                    Beyond its role in transportation, blood also serves crucial roles in defense and regulation. White
                    blood cells, a key component of blood, form the backbone of the immune system, defending the body
                    against harmful pathogens such as bacteria, viruses, and fungi. Blood also helps regulate body
                    temperature, pH levels, and fluid balance, ensuring optimal conditions for cellular function.
                    Moreover, blood clotting mechanisms prevent excessive bleeding and promote wound healing,
                    safeguarding the body against life-threatening hemorrhages. In essence, blood is the life force that
                    sustains human existence, underscoring its profound importance in maintaining health and vitality.
                </h4>
